# Approach
Iterate through all possible elements in both arrays, check whether 2 previous element is equal to 10, and then determine the calculation. Be careful with edge case handling, for example when there's only one entry.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
>Because this code only uses three integer variables, which counts as O(1) regardless of operation. And there's no other dynamic data structures like array except the input arrays. The input array is not considered as space complexity of this code chunk becaue it's part of the input. The space complexity analysis typically focuses on the additional space (beyond the input) that an algorithm uses to produce its result. 

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int isWinner(int[] player1, int[] player2) {
        int p1 = 0, p2 = 0;
        int len = player1.length;

        // If there's only 1 turn
        if (len == 1) {
            p1 += player1[0];
            p2 += player2[0];
            return p1 > p2 ? 1 : (p2 > p1 ? 2 : 0);
        }

        // For all turns except the first
        for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
            if (player1[i-1] == 10 || (i-2 >= 0 && player1[i-2] == 10)) {
                p1 += player1[i]*2;
            } else {
                p1 += player1[i];
            }

            if (player2[i-1] == 10 || (i-2 >= 0 && player2[i-2] == 10)) {
                p2 += player2[i]*2;
            } else {
                p2 += player2[i];
            }
        }

        // Handle the first turn
        p1 += player1[0];
        p2 += player2[0];

        return p1 > p2 ? 1 : (p2 > p1 ? 2 : 0);
    }
}

